<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-06T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-06T13:00:00-05:00" n="852" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d852">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11471: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul General at Shanghai</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-06T13:00:00-05:00">December 6, 1937—1
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>617. Your 1089, December 5, 10 a.m., just received. If the Japanese
                                are willing to withdraw the memorandum would it not be practicable
                                    <pb facs="0775" n="768" xml:id="pg_768"/> for the Commissioner
                                of Police to withdraw his report to the Municipal Council.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>